do you use.

00:02:12.530 --> 00:02:15.810
So, this idea has been
around for awhile.

00:02:15.810 --> 00:02:20.620
So in 1889, Arrhenius plotted
rate constants versus

00:02:20.620 --> 00:02:25.780
temperature, and he found that
if he plotted the natural log

00:02:25.780 --> 00:02:30.200
of those rate constants versus
inverse temperature, then he

00:02:30.200 --> 00:02:32.320
would get a straight line.

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:37.390
So let's look at the
plot that he had.

00:02:37.390 --> 00:02:40.570
So, he found that if he plotted
natural log of the

00:02:40.570 --> 00:02:44.080
rate constants versus 1 over
temperature, so units or

00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:47.440
kelvin to the minus 1, that
he got a straight line.

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:50.070
Which means that the rate
constants are varying

00:02:50.070 --> 00:02:52.610
exponentially with inverse
temperature.

00:02:52.610 --> 00:02:55.470
So you have to use a natural log
to get a straight line, if

00:02:55.470 --> 00:02:57.080
you don't use natural log,
you wouldn't get a

00:02:57.080 --> 00:02:59.220
straight line here.

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:02.170
So, let's look at some of these
terms that we have here,

00:03:02.170 --> 00:03:05.440
and here's our equation for the
straight line, the natural

00:03:05.440 --> 00:03:11.830
log of k equals minus e a -- e
a is activation energy, which

00:03:11.830 --> 00:03:15.410
we're going to talk a lot about
today -- over r t, r is

00:03:15.410 --> 00:03:19.280
our friend the gas constant,
and t is temperature, plus

00:03:19.280 --> 00:03:21.430
natural log of a.

00:03:21.430 --> 00:03:22.530
So what is a?

00:03:22.530 --> 00:03:25.760
A is called factor a or
sometimes it's called

00:03:25.760 --> 00:03:31.190
pre-exponential factor, and had
has the same units as k, k

00:03:31.190 --> 00:03:34.320
being the rate constant.

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:40.570
So, let's think about this
equation and this plot, and

00:03:40.570 --> 00:03:45.070
about factor A and this other
term, activation energy.

00:03:45.070 --> 00:03:49.690
So, factor A and activation
energy depend on the reaction

00:03:49.690 --> 00:03:50.620
being studied.

00:03:50.620 --> 00:03:53.380
So, it depends on the nature
of the materials involved.

00:03:53.380 --> 00:03:56.860
So I said we'd talk again about
nature of the material.

00:03:56.860 --> 00:03:59.970
So one kind of reaction's going
to have one activation

00:03:59.970 --> 00:04:04.070
energy, another one will
have a different one.

00:04:04.070 --> 00:04:05.860
So, let's think about
this term, factor

00:04:05.860 --> 00:04:08.880
A. What is it exactly?

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:12.080
Do you think it would be
temperature dependent?

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:12.490
What do you think?

00:04:12.490 --> 00:04:14.190
How many people think
yes, it would

00:04:14.190 --> 00:04:16.900
be temperature dependent?

00:04:16.900 --> 00:04:20.310
How many people think no?

00:04:20.310 --> 00:04:25.100
Some people are not
going to commit.

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:26.800
The answer is no.

00:04:26.800 --> 00:04:30.370
So, let's think about
what factor A is.

00:04:30.370 --> 00:04:35.450
So, factor A is the rate
constant at some really,

00:04:35.450 --> 00:04:38.830
really large temperature.

00:04:38.830 --> 00:04:42.960
So, if we look at this plot,
the natural log of k equals

00:04:42.960 --> 00:04:47.330
the natural log of A, or
k equals A if you're

00:04:47.330 --> 00:04:49.030
along this axis here.

00:04:49.030 --> 00:04:52.130
If you're along that axis
here, that's at zero, so

00:04:52.130 --> 00:04:57.420
