00:11:06.920 --> 00:11:09.360
All right, so activation energy,
we're going to be

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:11.470
talking a lot about
this today.

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:14.630
So, what is it exactly.

00:11:14.630 --> 00:11:19.600
So let's think about two
molecules coming together.

00:11:19.600 --> 00:11:22.470
So when two molecules come
together, you have this

00:11:22.470 --> 00:11:27.630
bimolecular process going on,
but every time two molecules

00:11:27.630 --> 00:11:29.210
come together, they're
not going to go

00:11:29.210 --> 00:11:31.650
on and form a product.

00:11:31.650 --> 00:11:36.970
You're only going to form a
product when those molecules

00:11:36.970 --> 00:11:39.620
have a critical amount
of energy.

00:11:39.620 --> 00:11:44.440
When they have the energy which
allows them to react,

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:46.270
that activation energy.

00:11:46.270 --> 00:11:49.180
If they have enough energy when
they come together, they

00:11:49.180 --> 00:11:51.960
will go on and form products.

00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:54.580
So, that's what activation
energy is, it's this critical

00:11:54.580 --> 00:11:59.440
amount of energy that they need
to react with each other.

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:03.120
All right, so let's just think
about what affects that

00:12:03.120 --> 00:12:06.240
critical amount of energy, and
of course, temperature is

00:12:06.240 --> 00:12:07.910
going to be involved.

00:12:07.910 --> 00:12:13.300
So let's think about that.

00:12:13.300 --> 00:12:23.220
So if we have fraction of
molecules on one side, and we

00:12:23.220 --> 00:12:30.430
have kinetic energy down here,
let's think about how

00:12:30.430 --> 00:12:32.130
temperature is involved
in this.

00:12:32.130 --> 00:12:38.040
So, at a low temperature, the
fraction of molecules that are

00:12:38.040 --> 00:12:43.620
going to have enough energy to
react is going to be less.

00:12:43.620 --> 00:12:47.890
And let's think about at a
higher temperature, go like

00:12:47.890 --> 00:12:54.510
this, so this is high
temperature, and we have low

00:12:54.510 --> 00:12:56.510
temperature up here.

00:12:56.510 --> 00:13:01.210
And then over here we would have
our activation energy,

00:13:01.210 --> 00:13:04.150
the energy needed
for a reaction.

00:13:04.150 --> 00:13:07.530
And you see, if you're at low
temperature, only a small

00:13:07.530 --> 00:13:11.050
number of molecules are going
to have enough energy to

00:13:11.050 --> 00:13:16.480
react, but if you're at higher
temperature, a large number of

00:13:16.480 --> 00:13:20.900
molecules are going to have that
critical energy to react.

00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:24.060
So, at low temperature, not
many can react, at higher

00:13:24.060 --> 00:13:27.250
temperature, many more will have
that energy -- will be

00:13:27.250 --> 00:13:31.570
able to overcome that activation
energy, will have

00:13:31.570 --> 00:13:34.320
it and they can react.

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:38.510
So, temperature plays
a big role here.

00:13:38.510 --> 00:13:42.850
So we can use this idea of
activation energy to predict a

00:13:42.850 --> 00:13:46.070
rate constant.

00:13:46.070 --> 00:13:49.100
Let's look at an example.

00:13:49.100 --> 00:13:56.000
So, often people have sucrose
in their diet, and the

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:00.370
hydrolysis of sucrose will form
glucose and fructose as

00:14:00.370 --> 00:14:02.790
part of this digestive
process.

00:14:02.790 --> 00:14:06.320
And we can think about the
rates at which that would

00:14:06.320 --> 00:14:07.880
happen in the body.

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:11.940
So normally, we're at 37
degrees, that's normal body

00:14:11.940 --> 00:14:15.600
temperature, and we have the
observed rate constant for

00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:16.540
that is 1 .

00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:20.590
0 times 10 to the minus 3
per molar per second.

00:14:20.590 --> 00:14:24.030
But what happens if your body
temperature is lowered, what

00:14:24.030 --> 00:14:29.150
happens if it was at 35 degrees,
and to be able to

00:14:29.150 --> 00:14:32.410
answer that question, you need
to know what the activation

00:14:32.410 --> 00:14:35.830
energy is for this process,
and here it's 108

00:14:35.830 --> 00:14:41.050
kilojoules per mole.

00:14:41.050 --> 00:14:44.180
So, we want to ask the question,
what is the new rate

00:14:44.180 --> 00:14:47.060
constant at 35 degrees?

00:14:47.060 --> 00:14:52.050
So, we can take our Arrhenius
equations, and we can put a 1

00:14:52.050 --> 00:14:55.280
by the rate constant for
temperature 1, and a 2 for the

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:57.760
rate constant at
temperature 2.

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:02.040
Now we can combine
these equations.

00:15:02.040 --> 00:15:05.860
Natural log of a cancels out,
it's not temperature dependent

00:15:05.860 --> 00:15:07.700
so it doesn't stay in here.

00:15:07.700 --> 00:15:11.860
And so we can solve, we can
subtract these two, or that's

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:16.400
equivalent to dividing them,
and so natural log of rate

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:20.530
constant 2 over rate constant 1
equals minus the activation

00:15:20.530 --> 00:15:25.460
energy over the gas constant
times this temperature term.

00:15:25.460 --> 00:15:27.330
Does this look at
all familiar?

00:15:27.330 --> 00:15:28.890
Does this look like some
other equation you

00:15:28.890 --> 00:15:31.740
saw once upon a time?

00:15:31.740 --> 00:15:35.450
Do you remember what that
equation was called?

00:15:35.450 --> 00:15:37.250
Van't Hoff equation, right.

00:15:37.250 --> 00:15:38.970
And there we were
comparing what

00:15:38.970 --> 00:15:41.930
instead of rate constants?

00:15:41.930 --> 00:15:45.210
Equilibrium constants, and
instead of e a, what term did

00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:47.140
we have here?

00:15:47.140 --> 00:15:49.100
Delta h, right.

00:15:49.100 --> 00:15:51.430
And it's good you remember that
because we're going to

00:15:51.430 --> 00:15:54.960
come back to that at the
end of today's class.

00:15:54.960 --> 00:15:57.890
So, we can use this equation
and plug in the values.

00:15:57.890 --> 00:16:01.230
We put in our activation energy,
and remember to pay

00:16:01.230 --> 00:16:03.950
attention to units, because if
you're going to cancel your

00:16:03.950 --> 00:16:06.740
joules with a gas constant, you
want to make sure you've

00:16:06.740 --> 00:16:10.980
converted your kilojoules to
joules, and then we can plug

00:16:10.980 --> 00:16:14.450
everything in and
solve for k 2.

00:16:14.450 --> 00:16:16.360
So, here k 2 is 7 .

00:16:16.360 --> 00:16:18.750
6 times 10 to the minus
4 per molar per

00:16:18.750 --> 00:16:20.930
second, so it's slower.

00:16:20.930 --> 00:16:23.710
And this is one reason why it's
really nice to have your

00:16:23.710 --> 00:16:26.730
body temperature stay the
normal temperature.

00:16:26.730 --> 00:16:30.830
If you get too cold, your body
processes, your enzymes are

00:16:30.830 --> 00:16:33.100
not functioning, everything
is slowed down.

00:16:33.100 --> 00:16:35.270
And if you get too hot, that's
